{"parse":{"title":"Manba Al-Ansab","pageid":42955281,"revid":824425612,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <i><b>Source of Genealogy</b></i>  or <i><b>Manba Al-Ans\u0101b</b></i> (Arabic: \u0645\u0646\u0628\u0639 \u0627\u0644\u0627\u0646\u0633\u0627\u0628 | Persian: \u0645\u0646\u0628\u0639 \u0627\u0646\u0633\u0627\u0628) is a historical document outlining various topics including the <a href=\"/wiki/Genealogy\" title=\"Genealogy\">genealogy</a> of the Sayyids of <a href=\"/wiki/Bukkur\" title=\"Bukkur\">Bukkur</a> (Urdu \u0628\u06be\u0627\u06a9\u0631\u06cc \u0633\u0627\u062f\u0627\u062a) and <a href=\"/wiki/Sufism\" title=\"Sufism\">Sufism</a> written by Sayyid Mu\u012bn Al-Haqq around 1426 <a href=\"/wiki/AD\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"AD\">AD</a> and the Islamic year 830. Sayyid Mu\u012bn is a notable <a href=\"/wiki/Sayyid\" title=\"Sayyid\">Sayyid</a> who descends from the Islamic prophet, <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad\" title=\"Muhammad\">Muhammad</a> through his descendant, <a href=\"/wiki/Ali_al-Hadi\" title=\"Ali al-Hadi\">Ali al-Hadi</a>. The work was extended by a lineal sixth degree descendant of Sayyid Mu\u012bn. Sayyid Ali Ghazanfar <a href=\"/wiki/Pseudonym\" title=\"Pseudonym\">alias</a> J\u0101rullah added more information other Sayyid ancestries and other <a href=\"/wiki/Sufi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sufi\">Sufi</a> orders. Sayyid Mu\u012bn lived in <a href=\"/wiki/India\" title=\"India\">India</a> where the book was originally written in <a href=\"/wiki/Persian_language\" title=\"Persian language\">Persian</a> and was later translated into <a href=\"/wiki/Urdu\" title=\"Urdu\">Urdu</a>. Manba Al-Ans\u0101b can also be found in the manuscript form in <a href=\"/wiki/The_British_Library\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"The British Library\">The British Library</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Allahabad\" title=\"Allahabad\">Allahabad</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/India\" title=\"India\">India</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Background\">Background</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Manba_Al-Ansab&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Background\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p><b>Sayyid Mu\u012bn</b> lived in <a href=\"/wiki/Jhusi\" title=\"Jhusi\">Jhusi</a> and belonged to the <a href=\"/wiki/Suhrawardiyya\" title=\"Suhrawardiyya\">Suhrawardiyya</a> Sufi order. He would often spend his time travelling and learning. His ancestors originally came from <a href=\"/wiki/Bukkur\" title=\"Bukkur\">Bukkur</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Sindh\" title=\"Sindh\">Sindh</a>, which was the home of Sayyids of Bukkur and settled in Jhusi where they established a centre for the propagation of <a href=\"/wiki/Islam\" title=\"Islam\">Islam</a>. In the course of his wanderings, he set out to ascertain and authenticate his ancestry which connected to <a href=\"/wiki/Ali_al-Hadi\" title=\"Ali al-Hadi\">Ali al-Hadi</a>. He went to Bukkur, the home of his ancestors and obtained a certificate of his pedigree from relatives who are from the same line of descent. Sayyid Mu\u012bn was shown a family tree of ancestry which was brought from <a href=\"/wiki/Mashhad\" title=\"Mashhad\">Mashhad</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Iran\" title=\"Iran\">Iran</a> to Sindh by <a href=\"/wiki/Sayyid_Muhammad_Al-Makki\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sayyid Muhammad Al-Makki\">Sayyid Muhammad Al-Makki</a>, the common ancestor of all Bukkuri\n/Bhakri Sayyids(Urdu: \u0628\u0647\u0627\u0643\u0631\u064a \u0633\u0627\u062f\u0627\u062a), on which he based this book. He outlined the essentials of <a href=\"/wiki/Sufism\" title=\"Sufism\">Sufism</a> and also made an account of the Sayyids of Bukkur and Allahabad.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Content\">Content</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Manba_Al-Ansab&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Content\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The book is divided into eleven chapters:<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>1) Genealogy of <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad\" title=\"Muhammad\">Muhammad</a>\n</p><p>2) Genealogy of the <a href=\"/wiki/Prophet\" title=\"Prophet\">Prophets</a>\n</p><p>3) History of <a href=\"/wiki/Muhammad\" title=\"Muhammad\">Muhammad</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/The_Twelve_Imams\" title=\"The Twelve Imams\">The Twelve Imams</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/The_Fourteen_Infallibles\" title=\"The Fourteen Infallibles\">The Fourteen Infallibles</a>\n</p><p>4) Account of the Sayyids of <a href=\"/wiki/Bukkur\" title=\"Bukkur\">Bukkur</a> and elsewhere\n</p><p>5) Account of various <a href=\"/wiki/Sufi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sufi\">Sufi</a> orders\n</p><p>6) Rules, observances and the prayers of <a href=\"/wiki/Sufi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sufi\">Sufi</a>\n</p><p>7) Doctrines of Philosophers and the <a href=\"/wiki/Sufi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sufi\">Sufi</a> regarding the soul\n</p><p>8) <a href=\"/wiki/Hadith\" title=\"Hadith\">Hadith</a> relating to <a href=\"/wiki/Sufism\" title=\"Sufism\">Sufism</a>\n</p><p>9) The meaning of the words, \"\u0100mantu Bill\u0101h\" (Arabic:\u0622\u0645\u0646\u062a \u0628\u0627\u0644\u0644\u0647)\n</p><p>10) Eulogies on <a href=\"/wiki/The_Twelve_Imams\" title=\"The Twelve Imams\">The Twelve Imams</a>\n</p><p>11) The origin and destiny of man\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Manba_Al-Ansab&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Persian Literature: A Bio-Bibliographical Survey</i>, Volume 1, Part 2</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Dictionary of Indo-Persian Literature</i>, Page 431</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><i>Persian Literature: A Bio-Bibliographical Survey</i>, Volume 1, Part 2, Page 949</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2227\nCached time: 20180921001106\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.044 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.062 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 144/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 326/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 78/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 937/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.009/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 670 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   36.719      1 -total\n 61.69%   22.653      1 Template:Reflist\n 38.09%   13.986      1 Template:Italic_title\n  5.03%    1.847      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:42955281-0!canonical and timestamp 20180921001106 and revision id 824425612\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"","*":"Genealogy"},{"sortkey":"","*":"Kinship_and_descent"},{"sortkey":"","*